2 GO analysis

2.1 Procedure of annotation

We will follow the procedure described here *http://www-huber.embl.de/users/klaus/Teaching/DESeq2Predoc2014.html#gene-ontology-enrichment-analysis*

using the library topGO.

The function genefinder from the r Biocpkg(“genefilter”) package will be used to find background genes that are similar in expression to the differentially expressed genes. The function tries to identify 10 genes for each DE–gene that match its expression strength.

We then check whether the background has roughly the same distribution of average expression strength as the foreground by plotting the densities.

We do this in order not to select a biased background since the gene set testing is performed by a simple Fisher test on a 2x2 table, which uses only the status of a gene, i.e. whether it is differentially expressed or not and not its fold–change or absolute expression.

Note that the chance of a gene being identified as DE will most probably depend on its gene expression for RNA–Seq data (potentially also its gene length etc.). Thus it is important to find a matching background. Our testing approach here is very similar to web tools like DAVID, however, we explicitly model the background here.

We first get average gene expressions for each of the genes and then find non–DE genes that show a similar expression as the DE–genes. These genes are then our background.

2.2 Get a list of GO per locus

blast2GO_mapping_split=split(x = blast2GO2, f = blast2GO2$locus)

geneID2GO=lapply(blast2GO_mapping_split, FUN = function(x){
  
  GOs=strsplit(as.character(x$GOs), split = ";", fixed = T)
  
  GOs=lapply(GOs, FUN = function(x) {
    res=sub(pattern = "C:", replacement = "" , x = x)
    res=sub(pattern = "P:", replacement = "" , x = res)
    res=sub(pattern = "F:", replacement = "" , x = res)
    return(res)
    })
  
  GOs=unlist(GOs)
  GOs=unique(GOs)
  return(GOs)
})

2.3 identify background genes for abdomen

overallBaseMean <- as.matrix(blast2GO2[, "baseMean.abdo", drop = F])

sig_idx = which(blast2GO2$locus %in% candidates_abdo)

backG_abdo <- c()

for(i in sig_idx){
  ind <- genefinder(overallBaseMean, i, 20, method = "manhattan")[[1]]$indices
  backG_abdo <- c(backG_abdo, ind)
  }

backG_abdo <- unique(backG_abdo)
backG_abdo <- blast2GO2$locus[backG_abdo]

# remove DE from background genes
backG_abdo <- setdiff(backG_abdo,  sig_idx)
length(backG_abdo)
## [1] 2302
backG_abdo_index=which(blast2GO2$locus %in% backG_abdo)

Plotting the density of the average expressions, shows that the background matching has worked reasonably well.

  multidensity( list( 
       all= log2(blast2GO2[,"baseMean.abdo"]) ,
       foreground =log2(blast2GO2[sig_idx, "baseMean.abdo"]), 
       background =log2(blast2GO2[backG_abdo_index, "baseMean.abdo"])), 
     xlab="log2 mean normalized counts", main = "Matching for enrichment analysis", xlim=c(0,15))

2.4 Identify background selection genes for head

overallBaseMean <- as.matrix(blast2GO2[, "baseMean.head", drop = F])

sig_idx = which(blast2GO2$locus %in% candidates_head)

backG_head <- c()

for(i in sig_idx){
  ind <- genefinder(overallBaseMean, i, 20, method = "manhattan")[[1]]$indices
  backG_head <- c(backG_head, ind)
  }

backG_head <- unique(backG_head)
backG_head <- blast2GO2$locus[backG_head]

# remove DE from background genes
backG_head <- setdiff(backG_head,  sig_idx)

     xlab="log2 mean normalized counts", main = "Matching for enrichment analysis", xlim=c(0,15))

We can now perform the actual testing. For this purpose we use the package which implements a nice interface to the Fisher–test based enrichment testing and also has additional algorithms taking the GO structure into account, by e.g. only reporting the most specific gene set in the hierarchy. For more details, see the paper:Alexa et. al. – Improved scoring of functional groups from gene expression data by decorrelating GO graph structure - Bioinformatics, 2006.

The GO has three top ontologies, cellular component (CC), biological processes (BP), and molecular function (MF). Here we test BP and MF subsequently.

Correlate the level of transcriptomic change with the phenotype

log2fold_head=read.table("../output/Log2Fold_head.txt")
log2fold_abdo=read.table("../output/Log2Fold_abdo.txt")
phenotypes=read.table("../data/phenotype.txt", h=T)
phenotypes=phenotypes$tabms.avg[phenotypes$Infection_status=="Inf"]


correlation_function=function(table=log2fold_head, phenotypes=phenotypes){
  res=NULL
  
  for (i in 1:dim(table)[1]){
    log2fold=table[i,]
    if (sum(is.na(log2fold))==0){
    test=cor.test(t(log2fold),phenotypes)
    res2=c(test$statistic, test$p.value)
    res=rbind(res,res2)
    }
    if (sum(is.na(log2fold))>0)
    {
      res2=c(NA, NA)
      res=rbind(res,res2)
    }
  }
  res=as.data.frame(res)
  names(res)=c("t", "p-value")
  row.names(res)=row.names(table)
  return(res)
  }

log2fold_head_correlations=correlation_function(table = log2fold_head, phenotypes=phenotypes)
log2fold_abdo_correlations=correlation_function(table = log2fold_abdo, phenotypes=phenotypes)
names(log2fold_head_correlations)=paste0("Pheno_H_", names(log2fold_head_correlations))
head(log2fold_head_correlations)

5 Add the correlation with phenotype to the table

final_tab = merge(x = final_tab, y = log2fold_head_correlations, by.x = "locus", by.y ="row.names")
final_tab = merge(x = final_tab, y = log2fold_abdo_correlations, by.x = "locus", by.y ="row.names")
